 explore, debate, lead, control, and resist. Using the late 1970s and early 1980s as an entree to the workings of China's "socialist literary system," the author shows how that system held sway from 1950 until around 1990, when an encroaching market economy gradually but fundamentally changed it. In addition to providing a definitive overview of how the socialist Chinese literary system worked, Link offers comparisons to the similar system in the Soviet Union. In the final chapter, the book seeks to explain how the word "good" was used and understood when applied to literary works in such systems. Combining aspects of cultural and literary studies, The Uses of Literature will reward anyone interested in the literature of modern China or how creativity is affected by a "socialist literary system."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / Chinese.2bisacsh  aAkhmatova, Anna.  aAlyoshin, Samuil.  aAnhui province.  aBai Hua.  aBai Xianyong.  aBell Tower Society.  aBureau of Drama Reform.  aCao Guanlong.  aCao Xueqin.  aChen Guokai.  aChinese Academy of Sciences.  aChinese Progress (journal).  aChristianity.  aConfucius.  aDai minority people.  aDemocracy Wall.  aEhrenburg, Ilya.  aFadeyev, Alexander.  aFeng Menglong.  aGao Xiaosheng.  aGuo Moruo.  aHan Shaogong.  aHeavy Wings (Zhang Jie).  aHiroshima.  aHu Yaobang.  aJiang Zilong.  aJin Jingmai.  aKhrushchev Remembers.  aKhrushchev, Nikita.  aKong Jiesheng.  aLi Yingru.  aMao Zedong.  aMarxism-Leninism.  aMay Fourth movement.  aNapoleon.  aPaustovsky, Konstantin.  aalienation.  abookstores.  abureaucratism.  acalligraphy.  acartoonists.  aconservatives.  acorruption.  adecadence.  ademocracy.  aengineering, literary.  aexistentialism.  afeudalism.  afilmscri